<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06226011 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06226011 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  A federal agency Monday ordered LTV Corp. to put money immediately into apension plan covering 70,000 current and retired employees because the agencysaid the fund was short $1.5 billion and it was in danger of running out ofmoney in October.;    The action was the latest in a long struggle between thegovernment, which wants LTV's retirees paid at the prevailing levels beforethe company filed a Chapter 11 bankruptcy petition in 1986, and LTV's manycreditors, who say the pension funds are getting too rich a share ofDallas-based LTV's assets.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  U.S. ORDERS LTV TO FUND PENSION PLAN  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Financial Digest  </MEMO><TEXT>     The order by the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp. would require LTV to makean immediate payment of $13.2 million.;    But LTV, the nation's third-largeststeel company and a major military contractor, said it could not comply withthe government's order without the approval of the Federal Bankruptcy Court.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910813  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  146  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday August 13, 199100226011,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>